SIMPLE: muscular
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muscular
<hw>Mus"cu*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>musculaire</ets>. See <er>Muscle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of
or pertaining to a muscle, or to a system of muscles; consisting of, or
constituting, a muscle or muscles; <as>as, <ex>muscular</ex>
fiber</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great <qex>muscular</qex> strength, accompanied by much
awkwardness.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Performed by, or dependent on, a muscle or the
muscles.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>muscular</xex> motion.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Well furnished with muscles; having well-developed
muscles; brawny; hence, strong; powerful; vigorous; <as>as, a
<ex>muscular</ex> body or arm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muscular Christian</b></col>, <cd>one who believes in a
part of religious duty to maintain a healthful and vigorous physical
state.</cd> <au>T. Hughes.</au> -- <col><b>Muscular
Christianity</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The practice and opinion of
those Christians who believe that it is a part of religious duty to
maintain a vigorous condition of the body, and who therefore approve of
athletic sports and exercises as conductive to good health, good morals,
and right feelings in religious matters.</cd> <au>T. Hughes.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An active, robust, and cheerful Christian life, as
opposed to a meditative and gloomy one.</cd> <au>C. Kingsley.</au> --
<col><b>Muscular excitability</b></col> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>that
property in virtue of which a muscle shortens, when it is stimulated;
irritability; contractility.</cd> -- <col><b>Muscular sense</b></col>
<fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>muscular sensibility; the sense by which we
obtain knowledge of the condition of our muscles and to what extent they
are contracted, also of the position of the various parts of our bodies
and the resistance offering by external objects.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscularity</ent>⟦br⟧
